comment.narrative:
1. Analysis further improving the renewable energy auction system based on international experience was prepared:
•	mechanism of auctions/auctions with prepared documentation, etc., indicating the pros and cons of each mechanism, including technology-neutral auctions.
•	requirements for participants (prequalification / tender obligations).
•	country-specific aspects (e.g.: grid connection requirements / energy balance requirements, etc.). 
•	requirements for the trading platform of auctions (electronic platform / standard trading mechanism, etc.). 
•	new trends in renewable energy auctions / promising aspects and developments.
The information was transferred to the Ministry of Energy.
2. The project had to reallocate some other resources to the next FY 2022, due to delays caused by the COVID-19 impact and extended revision and clearance processes over those activities planned for the implementation, being under an enhanced oversight framework. As recommended by the Mid-Term Review, the lessons learned and the experiences of the site-specific RE auctions supported by the project have to be studied and captured:
•	Legal, financial, technical and administrative aspects of the auctions will be analyzed;
•	Past auctions (2018-2020) analysis, based on the following criteria: simplicity and ease of the participants registering and of the process of bidding, access to information, reliability of the trading system;
•	Tariff indexing mechanism efficiency for the period between the auction completion (PPA concluding) and completion of the construction;
•	Development of alternative schemes for simplified transfer of the land plots for the site-specific auction winners.
This work will be submitted to the Ministry of Energy for further development of the RE auctions system, combined with the research of the international best practice, completed earlier.
Due to delays caused by COVID-19 and additional time needed for review, the work was moved to 2022
3. The planned work on modeling the implementation of renewable energy technology for managing electrical load (DEMAND RESPONSE) to balance the energy system of Kazakhstan - by the request of the national partner, was replaced by the work Feasibility Study Research of the existing potential of a flexible capacity and its inclusion in the energy balance by merging the Western Zone with the Unified Electric Power System of the Republic of Kazakhstan, providing for the integration of renewable energy facilities into the grid. , it is planned to be completed in 2022. That is, this is a system-wide research of the power supply system of the country with a specific focus on fixing the imbalances. Flexible capacities are a required pre-requisite for wider use of renewable capacities development, to back up unstable demand and also to cover load peaks, and this is an important issue for the Ministry of Energy of the RK.
4. The project had to reallocate some other resources to the next FY 2022, due to delays caused by the COVID-19 impact and extended revision and clearance processes over the activities planned for the implementation, being under an enhanced oversight framework.
•	Analysis of existing policies, rules for testing and certification of the RE systems components;
•	Analysis of existing standards, technical regulations, etc., (including the ones which were prepared with the assistance of the DREI project) for the RE components quality control;
•	Producing recommendations for creation or improvement of the regulatory base for the national testing system and certification, and testing protocols;
•	Analyzing current condition of quality testing analysis for Kazakhstan (presence of testing equipment) with the purpose to evaluate infrastructure of testing laboratories and needs for improvement, including the procedures and equipment needs;
•	Identifying the testing laboratories in Kazakhstan suitable for testing of the components of the RE systems, based on testing infrastructure research, including availability of relevant equipment.
The work started in 2021, but the time was limited to complete it the same year. In this regard, the work was moved to 2022
5. The project had to reallocate some other resources to the next FY 2022, due to delays caused by the COVID-19 impact and extended revision and clearance processes over the activities planned for the implementation, being under an enhanced oversight framework.
The work will concentrate on two aspects:
•	Agriculture as the user of the renewable energy;
•	Agriculture as a possible supplier of renewable energy.
For the first aspect, the needs and niches of possible application of RES in agriculture will be identified and recommendations on their support will be produced.
For the second aspect, resources available will be investigated (biomass), and needs for logistics, technologies and potential support to include the identified potential in the country’s energy system will be explored. This is a large-scale complex research, which will take a few months. Recommendations regarding potential support of the most promising technologies in the relevant niches will be developed.
The work started in 2021, but the time was limited to complete it the same year. In this regard, the work was moved to 2022.
6. The project had to reallocate some other resources to the next FY 2022, due to delays caused by the COVID-19 impact and extended revision and clearance processes over the activities planned for the implementation, being under an enhanced oversight framework. This assignment will include finding the most promising niches for the RE technologies application and relevant modelling, including modelling for the baseline technologies (non-RES) in the identical format for comparison. The LCOEs for the RE and non-RE technologies will be compared to identify the most promising niches. Recommendations regarding potential support of the most promising technologies in the relevant niches will be developed.
The work started in 2021, but the time was limited to complete it the same year. In this regard, the work was moved to 2022.
7. Economic analysis and developed of a financial support scheme under the law on net consumers for the development of a separate financial product was prepared:
•	Analysis of data to determine the parameters of a typical project of net consumer in Kazakhstan;
•	Modeling in MS Excel and analysis of a typical project based on the mentioned technology, within the life cycle (for solar PV with a capacity of up to 100 kW);
•	Description of factors contributing to the growth of demand, as well as barriers (legal, organizational, etc.) to the development of this niche, based on the results of modeling and consultations with participants in real projects, incl. while traveling;
•	Analysis of the economy of a typical project based on the technologies defined in the Action Plan, drawing up an opinion on the investment attractiveness of this technology, extrapolating the analysis to all regions of the country;
•	Analysis of the opportunities for introducing net metering for solar PV in Kazakhstan together with an explanation of advantages and disadvantages.
•	Recommendations for supporting the projects of the net consumer throughout the country;
•	Recommendations were produced aimed at supporting the net consumer through funding from various sources, including government funding and other relevant measures, including amendments in legislation.
Research of specific RES niches was recommended by the MTR, and based on that the project will work on a tailored support recommendations for this potentially wide segment of small-scale RES.
